<paragraph start="9" end="11">
<Alignment>1</Alignment>
<content start="9" end="10">
<component><class>org.concord.modeler.PageTextBox</class>
<width>750.0</width>
<height>150.0</height>
<title>&lt;html&gt;
  &lt;head&gt;
    
  &lt;/head&gt;
  &lt;body marginwidth=&quot;0&quot; marginheight=&quot;0&quot; face=&quot;verdana&quot;&gt;
    An electron is negatively charged. A nucleus contains protons that are 
    positively charged. There exists an electrostatic attraction between an 
    electron and a nucleus (also known as the Coulomb force). When they meet, 
    therefore, the electron is bound to the nucleus and an atom is formed.

    &lt;p&gt;
      Note that although an electron is very small, the size of an electron 
      cloud, which represents the area it may be in, is actually very 
      large--at least tens of thousands times larger than a nucleus. This is 
      why nuclei in our models are represented by a dot at which a plus sign 
      is drawn to indicate its positive charge.
    &lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;
</title>
<opaque>false</opaque>
</component></content>

